    "body": "<p class=\"article-lede\">Parents filled every seat in the Santa Rosa County School Board meeting room Thursday night as members voted to redraw attendance boundaries for the district's newest elementary school.</p><p>The board approved the redistricting plan 4-1, moving 340 students from Oriole Beach Elementary to the new Gulf Breeze Elementary School opening in August. The change affects families in the Tiger Point subdivision and areas east of Soundside Drive.</p><p>Santa Rosa County School Board member Karen Barber cast the lone opposing vote. She said the district should phase in the transition over two years to minimize disruption for families.</p><p>Superintendent Karen Barber told board members the new $28 million, 850-student facility will relieve overcrowding at three existing schools. Oriole Beach Elementary currently operates at 118 percent capacity with 647 students in a building designed for 550.</p><p>The redistricting followed three public hearings in December and January. More than 200 parents submitted written comments, with most opposing any boundary changes. Several families said moving schools would separate siblings or force longer bus rides.</p><p>The district will host orientation sessions in June for families transitioning to the new school. Students currently in fourth or fifth grade can choose to remain at their current school through graduation under a grandfather clause.</p><p>Construction crews are installing playground equipment and laying sod at the new campus on Tiger Point Boulevard. The facility includes 42 classrooms, a media center and a cafeteria serving 300 students per lunch period.</p>",
