    "body": "<p class=\"article-lede\">A backhoe tore into the asphalt on East Gadsden Street Monday morning as Pensacola began replacing stormwater pipes installed when Warren Harding was president.</p><p>The city awarded an $1.8 million contract to Gulf Coast Underground for the project covering 14 blocks in the East Hill neighborhood. Crews will replace clay pipes dating to the 1920s with modern concrete drainage systems over the next six months.</p><p>Pensacola Public Works Director Jon Jeffries said the old pipes collapsed in multiple locations, causing street flooding during heavy rain. Water pooled six inches deep on East Gadsden Street during storms last summer.</p><p>The project runs from 12th Avenue to 17th Avenue between Belmont and Cervantes Streets. Contractors will work on one block at a time, maintaining access to homes and businesses throughout construction.</p><p>The city received a $1.2 million federal infrastructure grant covering two-thirds of project costs. Stormwater utility fees paid by property owners fund the remaining balance.</p><p>Workers will install 7,200 linear feet of new pipe ranging from 18 to 36 inches in diameter. The system connects to an existing drainage canal that empties into Bayou Texar.</p><p>Pensacola completed similar pipe replacement projects in Eastside and North Hill neighborhoods over the past three years. The city maintains 450 miles of stormwater pipes across 42 square miles.</p>",
